725725f.title: Queens: 94th Street - 23rd Avenue
725725f.text:
94th Street (0ld Bowery Road), west side, north of Twenty-third
Ave., showing in the center of the view the Abraham Rapelye house,
demolished in 1934. This house was erected about 1750 by Daniel
Rapelje and has been known as the D.P. Rapelje house.
About 1932.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

725727f-d.title: Queens: 94th Street - 23rd Avenue
725727f-d.text:
94th Street, west side, ahout 450 ft. north of Twenty-
third Avenue, shoxing four views of the Ahraham Rapelye house
of 1852. These views are taken looking south from Ditmars
Boulevard. This section of 94th Street is the original Old
Bowery Road. Simon Remsen (b. 1748) married a daughter of
Daniel Rapelye and occupied this farm. His daumhter married
James Strong whose heirs owned it ir 1881. See other views for
more data.
May 1923

View 4: May 1929

725726f-a.title: Queens: 94th Street - 23rd Avenue
725726f-a.text:
4th Street, west side, about 450 feet, north of Twenty-
third Avenue, showing four views of the Abraham Rapelye farmhouse
and outhildiigs. This house was probably erected by Capt. Thoras
Hagard shortly after 1724. This farm and the buildings were ovned
and occupied bv members of the Rapelye familv from 1787 to 1896.
The history of this area is that Thomas Stevenson had a patent
in 1651 on the Rev. Francis Doughtv farm vhich lay between the
Old Bowerv Road and Flushing Bay and south of Mill Creek or as
it is also known as Jackson Greek. In 1787 it became the property
of Abraham Rapelye. He built a dock on Flushing Bav just south
of the mouth of Jacksonk Creek which in thos davs Was probably
at 96t Street, and s outh of this house between Old Bowery Bay Rd.
and the Hazard tract which was also purchased by Daniel Rapelve.
It was later known as Strongs farm; it being the property of
Aletta Rapelve Strong. The successive owners that followed Nere
Wm. W. Thomas, Dr. Oliver Jones of Cold Spring Harbor,ard the
Navahoe Realty Company. The Doughty house stood on the shore
of Flushing Bay on a lare made by Dr. Adrian Van der Douck. IIt
was the house of tNe Rapelye, Remsen and Strong farilies and was
located at or near the present site of the Strong residence. The
wing of the Ranelye house collapsed in November 1933 and the
buildinm was demolished in March 1934.
